There were approximately 170,000 abortions carried out in Togo between 2015 and 2017 alone. Alternative options for an unplanned pregnancy are limited despite attempts to encourage adoption. “[T]he child adoption process is slow and intrusive.” There are lengthy delays, waiting limits, and the women interested in adoptive child do not prefer children born through rape or infanticide. Thus, “when they are unable to spend time and energy on adoption, women make the difficult decision of raising the child because of social pressure and the culture of the country[.]”

In the construction village of Kalauwey, a 19-year old from Togo undertook the choice of placing her baby up for birth. She was young and unprepared for the responsibility of a nation. The government, though, had other plans for the infant. Following her basic, informed, consent, the government ordered adoption. This not only ignored her voice but driven the economic burden onto her future.

Surprisingly, this adoption is treated as legal in the Country. Abortion is illegal in all circumstances and the forced adoption remains a violation of the child’s right to name and family. When considering abortion, if a crime can be avoided, the Pregnancy Protection Program can be met, with the consent of both the parents, family members, and the Ministry of Social Affairs headed by the Government.
